      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Undeparted</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dennis Aftergut letter comments on Noah Feldman's April 8 article on US options in Iraq</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Noah Feldman (April 8) has it right: With no desirable option apparent for Iraq, leaders of both parties are in the dysfunctional mode of avoiding blame. But his ''solution'' -- re-branding the conflict as a fight with Al Qaeda while endorsing no change in strategy -- is a recipe for more of the same.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Noah Feldman (April 8) has it right: With no desirable option apparent for Iraq, leaders of both parties are in the dysfunctional mode of avoiding blame. But his ''solution'' -- re-branding the conflict as a fight with Al Qaeda while endorsing no change in strategy -- is a recipe for more of the same.</p>
        <p>Feldman hints at one proposal with promise: a subdivided Iraq, though only if Iraq's neighbors and the United States can force the sharing of oil revenues (a concept already prescribed by the Iraqi Constitution). This scenario would require keeping American troops in the Sunni region to support tribal leaders battling Al Qaeda. Another likely requirement would be the relocation of Baghdad's remaining Sunnis -- a process that death squads will otherwise complete.</p>
        <p>The current approach, however rebranded, only postpones disaster at the cost of more lives and treasure.</p>
        <p>Dennis Aftergut</p>
        <p>Lake Placid, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
